	<!-- open content container -->

<div align="center">
	<div class="page" style="width:100%; text-align:left">
		<div style="padding:0px 25px 0px 25px">

	<div id="edit762887" style="padding:0px 0px 6px 0px">
	<!-- this is not the last post shown on the page -->	


<table id="post762887" class="tborder" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center">
<tr>
	
		<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" >		
			<!-- status icon and date -->
			<a name="post762887"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/legacy_images/statusicon/post_old.gif" alt="Old" border="0" /></a>
			September 14th, 2005, 10:33 AM
			
			<!-- / status icon and date -->				
		</td>
		<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" align="right">
			&nbsp;
			&nbsp;
			#<a href="showpost.php?s=41bd162d6c92e079ba6a958c8e6a7f1f&amp;p=762887&amp;postcount=13" target="new" rel="nofollow" id="postcount762887" name="13"><strong>13</strong></a>
			
		</td>
	
</tr>
<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175">
	
	
			<div id="postmenu_762887">
				
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?s=41bd162d6c92e079ba6a958c8e6a7f1f&amp;u=9305">Niccolo</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_762887", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Forum Channeler</div>
			
			
		
			
			
			
						
			
			<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
				
				
				
				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>   </div>
			</div>				
	
	
	
	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_762887">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_762887"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>DigitalDemon</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">To me, it feels like they are still in the Diablo 2 and Warcraft 3 balancing mindset. Nerf things each patch while buffing others to enable/disable certain builds/playstyles and encourage people to reroll (I HATED this in D2, and to a lesser extent in W3) just because you'll find something you like or enjoy playing/doing and then they change everything and you have to start over. Usually it was some other strategy getting nerfed that took one piece of your strategy out.<br />
<br />
It's shotgun blast balancing, fire off a huge spread and see what sticks. Who cares if it breaks everything in between!</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
 Precisely. This is what drives a lot of the mindset at Blizzard, I feel. There's nothing wrong with it, because Diablo and Warcraft 3 were unparalleled successes even in an age of extremely competitive RPGs and RTS games against which they competed. <br />
<br />
Spiffe,<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Spiffe</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Huh? You keep people interested in the game by presenting *new* challenges, not increasing the difficulty of ones they've already completed. It's, "Now that you've bested the dreaded dragon Onyxia, can you defeat Deathwing?", not "Now that you've bested Onyxia, we're going to change the encounter again to make it more difficult... can you defeat Onyxia 3.1?" That's no kind of fun.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Yeah, this is an ideal, but it's very far away from the reality. These companies operate on corporate budgets (and in Blizzard's case, Vivendi is breathing down their necks on a very regular, audit-driven basis, due to laws for publicly traded companies like the  Sarbanes Oxley Act, which require exhaustive accounting of where money is going), so like any organization with monitored, finite resources, they need to pick and choose their battles. There's insufficient bandwidth for this nonstop "add new stuff" that you're talking about, especially when some of the old stuff is just unbalanced. <br />
<br />
Classic example: Scholomance and Stratholme were both meant to be 5-manned, but they were really only 5-mann<b>able</b> after Nerf 1 (March) and then made very enjoyable in Nerf 2 (this past Summer). People who like a challenge whined and complained that it was too easy (and sure, Ras is a lot more like Araj now - but isn't Ras supposed to be solidly 5-manned by questers in this level range?). Without the focus and bandwidth to modify these instances, players would have remained very reluctant to 5-man them and the content would have remained mostly raid-only, which wasn't part of the original plan. <br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Nerfing Rank 1 spells is a *big* change that vastly affects caster gameplay. Was it really necessary? Did anyone think it was overpowered?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
You've got to be kidding me. You don't think it was completely abusive for people to load up on +dmg gear, and use rank 1 spells to outdamage their peers who were using their current rank spells? This is an unfortunate strategy that was built up around a totally flawed premise that doesn't even make sense from a gaming or fantasy perspective. "Stand back, Gimly," said Gandalf, as he raised his staff. "I'm going to kill the Balrog using my Level 1 Frostbolt, but don't worry, the Light of Anduril shall guide me to victory!" Epic challenges demand epic responses. It was a loophole that was being exploited, and it's about time they closed it.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				A nerf here, a nerf there, is unfortunate, but understandable. A nerf everywhere, all the time, is highly disruptive and causes a lot of strife within the playerbase. Do they just not care? I'm not yet to the point where I'm apathetic to advancing my character because I expect a nerf to anything good, but I can see the game heading down that path, and it's not a good one for customer retention.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
Read Digital Demon's piece if you want to see where we're headed. Blizzard routinely rebalances (even dramatically so) just for shits and giggles in an effort to force the players to rethink their choices. It's what makes a lot of games interesting - when the rules of engagement change midstream, it separates the great players from just the average time-grinders to see who can adapt and thrive, and who crashes and burns.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
		<img class="inlineimg" src="images/legacy_images/statusicon/user_offline.gif" alt="Niccolo is offline" border="0" />


		
		
		
		&nbsp;
	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" align="right">
	
