	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_762962">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_762962"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Niccolo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">I think you're still looking at the MMO business model as it existed during the Ultima Online and EverQuest ages. The ball game has really changed since WoW. It proves that you don't need long-lasting or enduring content in order to become the largest game, and suggests the possibility that replayability rather than sustainability may very well trump all considerations.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
I don't think it's changed that much at the high-end -- a grind is still a grind, and no fun when it suddenly gets obviated.  Just because it may be more enjoyable and feasible in WoW to level up alts doesn't mean that I'm going to like it any more when my "main" gets nerfed to hell.  At any rate, I certainly don't think the marketplace has changed so much that customer retention is of minor concern.<br />
<br />
The D2/WC3 point raised by Kraksul is an interesting one; based on the history of those games, Blizzard really may feel free to take a heavy hand at adjusting balancing issues as they see fit.  The key difference is that in WC3, it took a whole 15 minutes to work your way up to being able to cast Infernal -- you started fresh every time you played, so if they changed the gameplay you were able to roll with the changes much more easily.  People who spent months farming to get Invulnerable Mail aren't getting their time &amp; money back next time they log in.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Niccolo</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">You've got to be kidding me. You don't think it was completely abusive for people to load up on +dmg gear, and use rank 1 spells to outdamage their peers who were using their current rank spells? </div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
I'm not familiar with this scenario; I'm thinking about people using rank-1 interrupts/snares/roots in PvP.  In either case, no, I don't think it's abusive or inconsistent.  Why would it be?  A smart caster uses the best tool for the job.  From a fantasy/RP perspective, presumably the higher-rank versions are a more powerful incantation of the same spell; it's not like you forgot the previous one.  Gandalf presumably doesn't need to blow his whole mana pool tossing Rank 8 Pyroblasts on goblin yard trash.<br />
<br />
(Though personally, I think Gandalf's a big poseur -- the guy almost never casts spells!  What the hell kind of wizard spends all his time meleeing?  I bet that bridge collapsed simply because it was over its load limit.)</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
